CREATE TABLE table_name (
  column_name data_type [constraints],
  ...
);

Example:
CREATE TABLE Students (
  sid CHAR(20) PRIMARY KEY,
  name CHAR(30),
  login CHAR(20),
  age INTEGER
);

INSERT INTO table_name (col1, col2, ...)
VALUES (val1, val2, ...);

Example:
INSERT INTO Students (sid, name, email, age)
VALUES (53688, 'Smith', 'smith@ee', 18);

Note: Strings use single quotes; numbers do not.

ALTER TABLE table_name
ADD column_name data_type;

Example:
ALTER TABLE Students
ADD phone_number VARCHAR2(15);

Also used to: MODIFY (change data type), DROP COLUMN (remove a column)

DROP TABLE table_name;

Example:
DROP TABLE Students;

Important: This PERMANENTLY deletes the table schema AND all its data. It cannot be undone!

1. DML Privileges: INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE, SELECT
2. DDL Privileges: CREATE, ALTER, DROP
3. Administrative: ALL PRIVILEGES, GRANT OPTION

Grant all: GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES TO 'username';
Grant specific: GRANT INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE TO 'username';

CREATE TABLE GoldRate (
  rate_id INT PRIMARY KEY,
  rate_date DATE NOT NULL,
  price_per_tola DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL,
  price_per_10gm DECIMAL(10,2) NOT NULL
);

GRANT:
GRANT SELECT, INSERT ON Students TO 'alice';
GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON database.* TO 'admin';

REVOKE:
REVOKE INSERT ON Students FROM 'alice';

With grant option (user can grant to others):
GRANT SELECT ON Students TO 'alice' WITH GRANT OPTION;
